Add two tests that pin the pass-through behaviour:

```kotlin
@Test fun corruptionOccurred_reflectsInjectedState_true() {
  corruption.markCorruption() // or whatever setter AppCorruptionState exposes
  val vm = HomeViewModel(registry, corruption, logExport)
  assertTrue(vm.corruptionOccurred)
}

@Test fun corruptionOccurred_reflectsInjectedState_false() {
  val vm = HomeViewModel(registry, corruption, logExport) // fresh default = false
  assertFalse(vm.corruptionOccurred)
}
```
If AppCorruptionState has no public mutator, construct one via its test-visible API or use a tiny test subclass exposing the flag. Without the `true` case the test suite accepts any constant — the banner's seed is the only gate between a real corruption event and the UI surfacing it.

Replace the real LogExportManager with a test double that records buildExport + writeTo calls and can throw IOException on demand. Two tests:

```kotlin
@Test fun buildAndWrite_success_delegatesToLogExportManager() = runTest {
  val fake = RecordingLogExport()
  val vm = HomeViewModel(registry, corruption, fake)
  val uri = Uri.parse("content://foo")
  val result = vm.buildAndWrite(uri)
  assertTrue(result.isSuccess)
  assertEquals(ExportSource.About, fake.lastSource)
  assertEquals(uri, fake.lastUri)
  assertEquals(fake.builtContent, fake.writtenContent) // proves write uses buildExport output
}

@Test fun buildAndWrite_ioException_returnsFailure() = runTest {
  val fake = RecordingLogExport().apply { writeThrows = IOException("disk full") }
  val vm = HomeViewModel(registry, corruption, fake)
  val result = vm.buildAndWrite(Uri.parse("content://foo"))
  assertTrue(result.isFailure)
  assertTrue(result.exceptionOrNull() is IOException)
}
```
Mock change: extract a RecordingLogExport fake in this file rather than constructing the real LogExportManager — the current setUp instantiates the real one solely to satisfy the ctor and comments that tests "never call buildAndWrite", which is a tell that the coverage is missing.

Give FakeWarmupCoordinator a dedicated CoroutineScope stored as a property, and cancel it in @After:

```kotlin
private class FakeWarmupCoordinator(val ownScope: CoroutineScope) : WarmupCoordinator(
  registry = FakeModelRegistry(mutableListOf()),
  appSettings = FakeAppSettingsRepository(),
  errorLog = ErrorLog(ApplicationProvider.getApplicationContext<Application>()),
  scope = ownScope,
) { ... }

// in test class:
private val fakeScopeJob = SupervisorJob()
private val fakeScope = CoroutineScope(fakeScopeJob + Dispatchers.Unconfined)
@Before fun setUp() { ...; fakeWarmupCoordinator = FakeWarmupCoordinator(fakeScope) }
@After fun tearDown() { Dispatchers.resetMain(); fakeScopeJob.cancel() }
```
Alternatively, prefer composition over inheritance — declare WarmupCoordinator as an `interface` (or extract one) and let the fake implement it without inheriting the init block. This is strictly cleaner but a larger refactor.
